    "text": "[@keks](@YXkE3TikkY4GFMX3lzXUllRkNTbj5E+604AkaO1xbz8=.ed25519) \n\n> If you want to use the flexibility this gives you (say, floating divs)\n\nI'd only interested in using HTML encoding structure and semantics, not styles. There are two main benefits:\n\n- more useful semantics (audio, video, abbr, etc)\n- fewer edge-cases where humans and machines disagree\n\nConsider the following Markdown:\n\n```markdown\n- a\n - b\n  - c\n   - d\n    - e\n     - f\n      - g\n       - h\n        - i\n         - j\n```\n\nFrom a plaintext perspective, it looks like a recursively nested list. \n\nThe [CommonMark dingus](https://spec.commonmark.org/dingus/) thinks that should render as:\n\n> - a\n> - b\n> - c\n> - d - e\n>     - f \n>     - g\n>     - h\n>     - i - j\n\nGitHub disagrees, and renders it as:\n\n> - a\n> - b\n> - c\n> - d  \n>   -‍ e\n>     - f\n>     - g\n>     - h\n>     - i\n>\n>       -‍‍ j\n\n\nMarkdown standardization has vastly improved in the past decade, but in my opinion it's **still not good enough** for encoding document structure in p2p systems. I like subjectivity and I'm happy to embrace it in many contexts, but I'd prefer to avoid it when encoding our document structure / semantics. \n\n> So there *will* be an ssb-markdown - even if it’s just used on the composing side.\n\n+1 on this, and I should mention that I actually enjoy composing in Markdown, but I don't want ssb-markdown to be *required* for new clients and implementations. As always, clients that want to maintain full backward-compatibility with every Scuttlebutt post ever will *of course* need to implement the ssb-markdown rendering logic, but I'm sure that eventually we'll figure out [how to deprecate things](%PWLnDqu8DnmtN04COlkM7937xiP4fqEMS0hDEUqSlhs=.sha256).",
